<h2>The Problem</h2>

<p>Web Everything enforces <strong>conflict-free cohabitation</strong> across modules developed by different teams. The injector system provides scoped dependency resolution, registries provide dynamic naming, and blocks are tree-shakeable imports. But one critical piece escapes this scoping discipline: <strong>DOM events</strong>.</p>

<p>CustomEvent names are globally-scoped strings. Any module can dispatch any event name, and any ancestor can listen for it. This creates three distinct problems:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Name collisions</strong> &mdash; Two blocks from different teams using the same event name (e.g., <code>change</code>, <code>toggle</code>) with different semantics or detail shapes</li>
  <li><strong>Shared semantics</strong> &mdash; Multiple blocks legitimately needing the same event contract (e.g., <code>beforetoggle</code>/<code>toggle</code> is used by View, Popover API, and <code>&lt;details&gt;</code>) but with no way to formally declare adherence</li>
  <li><strong>Detail shape drift</strong> &mdash; No runtime enforcement of <code>event.detail</code> structure, so consumers must trust that producers send the right shape</li>
</ol>

<p>Convention-based naming (prefixing, etc.) is a valid last resort, but it represents <strong>giving up on providing a unified approach</strong> through Web Everything. Before resorting to convention, we want to explore two more ambitious axes: <strong>Symbol-based events</strong> (via new standard + polyfill) and <strong>listener discrimination</strong> (letting listeners filter by something other than name).</p>


<h2>Event Taxonomy</h2>

<p>Before solving scoping, we need clearer language for <em>what events are</em>. Today, DOM events conflate three fundamentally different communication patterns:</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th></th>
      <th>Notification</th>
      <th>Targeted Command</th>
      <th>Broadcast Command</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Intent</strong></td>
      <td>"This happened"</td>
      <td>"You, do this"</td>
      <td>"Everyone, do this"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Direction</strong></td>
      <td>Source &rarr; ancestors (bubbles up)</td>
      <td>Trigger &rarr; single target (directed)</td>
      <td>Source &rarr; descendants or all (trickles down / global)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>DOM examples</strong></td>
      <td><code>click</code>, <code>change</code>, <code>toggle</code>, <code>input</code></td>
      <td><code>CommandEvent</code> (Invoker Commands API)</td>
      <td>None &mdash; no standard pattern exists</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>In our codebase</strong></td>
      <td><code>tab-change</code>, <code>route-change</code>, <code>toggle</code></td>
      <td><code>--view-show</code>, <code>--view-hide</code>, <code>--view-toggle</code></td>
      <td>(not yet implemented)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cancelable?</strong></td>
      <td>Sometimes (to veto: <code>beforetoggle</code>)</td>
      <td>Yes (target can refuse)</td>
      <td>Possibly (any receiver could veto)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Collision risk</strong></td>
      <td><strong>High</strong> &mdash; many things "toggle"</td>
      <td>Low &mdash; directed to specific element by ID</td>
      <td><strong>High</strong> &mdash; "close" could mean many things</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>The Broadcast Command Gap</h3>

<p>The Invoker Commands API solves <em>targeted</em> commands: a button's <code>commandfor</code> attribute points at a specific element by ID. But some commands are inherently <strong>broadcast</strong> &mdash; they have no single target:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>"Close all modals"</strong> &mdash; every open modal should close. No single <code>commandfor</code> target.</li>
  <li><strong>"Pause all media"</strong> &mdash; every playing audio/video element should pause.</li>
  <li><strong>"Enter maintenance mode"</strong> &mdash; every interactive component should disable.</li>
  <li><strong>"Theme changed"</strong> / <strong>"Locale changed"</strong> &mdash; every affected component should re-render.</li>
  <li><strong>"Network offline"</strong> &mdash; every component with pending requests should show fallback state.</li>
</ul>

<p>These are imperative ("do this") like commands, but they propagate like notifications. They're <strong>commands without a target</strong>. The DOM has no standard pattern for this &mdash; today people use <code>window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('close-all-modals'))</code> or a pub/sub bus, both of which are globally-scoped strings with all the collision risks we're trying to solve.</p>

<p>Broadcast commands face the <strong>same collision problem</strong> as notifications. If Team A broadcasts <code>'close'</code> meaning "close modals" and Team B broadcasts <code>'close'</code> meaning "close sidebar panels", every listener for <code>'close'</code> fires for both. This is arguably worse than notification collisions because commands have side effects.</p>

<h3>Implications for Solutions</h3>

<p>Any event scoping solution must handle all three patterns, not just notifications:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Notifications</strong> &mdash; need listener discrimination (the core challenge below)</li>
  <li><strong>Targeted commands</strong> &mdash; handled by Invoker Commands API + <code>--</code> prefix</li>
  <li><strong>Broadcast commands</strong> &mdash; need both dispatch-side scoping (who broadcasts?) and listener-side discrimination (who responds?). This is the hardest case because there's no established DOM pattern to build on.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Terminology Questions</h3>

<p>We need clear vocabulary for these categories. Some options:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Notification / Command (targeted) / Command (broadcast)</strong> &mdash; precise but verbose</li>
  <li><strong>Signal / Command / Broadcast</strong> &mdash; "signal" overloaded (TC39 Signals proposal)</li>
  <li><strong>Emission / Invocation / Dispatch</strong> &mdash; precise, but unfamiliar</li>
  <li><strong>Event / Action / Announcement</strong> &mdash; "action" already means something in our project</li>
</ul>

<p>Whatever terms we choose, blocks should explicitly declare which type each of their events is, so documentation and tooling can treat them differently.</p>


