<h3>What Works Today</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Module-prefixed names</strong> &mdash; <code>tab-change</code>, <code>route-*</code> events are namespaced by convention</li>
  <li><strong>Standard-aligned names</strong> &mdash; <code>beforetoggle</code>/<code>toggle</code> deliberately match the Popover API shape</li>
  <li><strong>TypeScript interfaces</strong> &mdash; <code>ViewToggleEventDetail</code> and <code>TabChangeEventDetail</code> provide compile-time safety</li>
</ul>

<h3>What Doesn't Work</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>No runtime enforcement</strong> &mdash; A third-party block could dispatch <code>tab-change</code> with a completely different detail shape</li>
  <li><strong>No discoverability</strong> &mdash; Consumers have no way to query "what events does this element emit?"</li>
  <li><strong>No shared contract</strong> &mdash; View's <code>toggle</code> and Popover's <code>toggle</code> have the same shape by convention, not by contract</li>
  <li><strong>Bubbling collisions</strong> &mdash; If two nested elements both fire <code>toggle</code>, ancestors must manually check <code>event.target</code></li>
</ul>


