<h3>Symbols: The Raw Constraint</h3>

<p>The DOM spec requires <strong>DOMString</strong> for event types. Passing a Symbol to <code>addEventListener</code> or <code>new CustomEvent()</code> triggers Web IDL's <code>ToString()</code> coercion, which <strong>throws a TypeError</strong>. This is why every existing solution falls back to string conventions.</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Strings</th><th>Symbols</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>DOM API compatibility</td><td>Yes</td><td><strong>No</strong> (TypeError)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>JSON serialization</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DevTools visibility</td><td>Full</td><td>Not inspectable as event types</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Cross-realm (iframes)</td><td>Work</td><td><code>Symbol()</code> unique per realm; <code>Symbol.for()</code> shared cross-realm. Moot for DOM events &mdash; events don't cross iframe boundaries.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Name collision prevention</td><td>Requires conventions</td><td>Inherent uniqueness</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Node.js EventEmitter</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes (fully supported)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>But this project already patches browser APIs &mdash; that's what <strong>plugs</strong> are. Could a polyfill bridge the gap?</p>


<h3>Symbol Events via Polyfill: Feasibility Study</h3>

<p>A plug could patch <code>EventTarget.prototype.addEventListener</code> and <code>EventTarget.prototype.dispatchEvent</code> to accept Symbols, mapping them to unique strings under the hood:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// Symbol → unique string mapping
const symbolToString = new Map&lt;symbol, string&gt;();

function resolveType(type: string | symbol): string {
  if (typeof type === 'string') return type;
  if (!symbolToString.has(type)) {
    const desc = type.description ?? 'event';
    const id = crypto.randomUUID().slice(0, 8);
    symbolToString.set(type, `__sym:${desc}:${id}`);
  }
  return symbolToString.get(type)!;
}

// Patch addEventListener to accept Symbol types
const origAddEventListener = EventTarget.prototype.addEventListener;
EventTarget.prototype.addEventListener = function(type, listener, options) {
  return origAddEventListener.call(this, resolveType(type), listener, options);
};

// Patch dispatchEvent to accept Symbol-typed events
const origDispatchEvent = EventTarget.prototype.dispatchEvent;
EventTarget.prototype.dispatchEvent = function(event) {
  // Event already has a resolved string type from createEvent helper
  return origDispatchEvent.call(this, event);
};

// Helper to create events with Symbol types
function createEvent&lt;T&gt;(type: symbol, detail: T, init?: EventInit) {
  return new CustomEvent(resolveType(type), { ...init, detail });
}</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// Usage — collision-free by construction
export const TAB_CHANGE = Symbol('tab-change');
export const ROUTE_CHANGE = Symbol('route-change');

// Producer
element.dispatchEvent(createEvent(TAB_CHANGE, { from: 'a', to: 'b' }));

// Consumer — import the symbol to listen
import { TAB_CHANGE } from 'blocks/tabs';
element.addEventListener(TAB_CHANGE, (e) =&gt; { /* type-safe */ });</code></pre>

<h4>Polyfill trade-offs</h4>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Assessment</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Collision safety</strong></td>
      <td>Inherent &mdash; two Symbols are never equal even with same description</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Type safety</strong></td>
      <td>Full &mdash; Symbol + generics: <code>createEvent&lt;TabChangeDetail&gt;(TAB_CHANGE, detail)</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>DevTools</strong></td>
      <td>Degraded &mdash; Events Listeners panel shows <code>__sym:tab-change:a7f3b2</code> instead of human-readable name. Would need a DevTools extension to resolve back to Symbol descriptions.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cross-realm (iframes)</strong></td>
      <td>Not a real concern &mdash; <code>Symbol('x')</code> in frame A &ne; <code>Symbol('x')</code> in frame B, but this doesn't matter because DOM events don't cross iframe boundaries. Each iframe has its own document tree; events dispatched inside stay inside. Iframe communication uses <code>postMessage</code> (serialized data), not DOM events.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Declarative HTML</strong></td>
      <td>Incompatible &mdash; can't write <code>on:click="Symbol(handleClick)"</code> in markup. See "When Strings Are Essential" below.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Standardisation path</strong></td>
      <td>The polyfill proves the concept. Could inform a proposal to extend <code>addEventListener</code> to accept Symbols natively &mdash; Node.js already does this. But browser adoption timeline would be years.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Micro-frontend safety</strong></td>
      <td>A late-loading micro-frontend with its own <code>Symbol('tab-change')</code> gets a <em>different</em> symbol automatically &mdash; no collision, no throw. This is a strength over string registries where a late registrant would clash.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h4>Open design questions for Symbol approach</h4>
<ul>
  <li>Should the resolved string be deterministic (from <code>Symbol.for()</code>) or random (from <code>Symbol()</code>)? Random provides stronger isolation.</li>
  <li>How to handle <code>removeEventListener</code>? Must resolve the same string for the same Symbol &mdash; the <code>Map</code> handles this.</li>
  <li>Can we provide a DevTools integration (via <code>__devtools_symbol_map__</code> global) so browser tooling can display meaningful names?</li>
  <li>Does patching <code>EventTarget.prototype</code> conflict with other polyfills or libraries?</li>
</ul>


<h3>When String Events Are Essential</h3>

<p>Not everything can move to Symbols. Some use cases fundamentally require string-based event names:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Declarative HTML attributes</strong> &mdash; <code>on:click="save"</code>, <code>onclick="handler()"</code>, Alpine's <code>x-on:click</code>, HTMX's <code>hx-trigger</code>. Markup is strings. You can't write a Symbol in an HTML attribute.</li>
  <li><strong>DevTools</strong> &mdash; The Event Listeners panel, <code>monitorEvents()</code>, and Performance timeline all display and filter by string names.</li>
  <li><strong>Event delegation</strong> &mdash; Patterns where a single ancestor listener matches <code>event.type</code> against a string table: <code>switch(e.type) { case 'click': ... }</code></li>
  <li><strong>SSR / Hydration</strong> &mdash; Server-rendered HTML includes event binding instructions as string attributes. Symbols only exist at runtime.</li>
  <li><strong>Browser native events</strong> &mdash; The browser will always fire <code>click</code>, <code>change</code>, <code>toggle</code>, <code>beforetoggle</code> as strings. A Symbol approach can't replace these &mdash; only custom events.</li>
  <li><strong>MutationObserver</strong> &mdash; Attribute observation and DOM inspection work with strings.</li>
</ul>

<p>This suggests a <strong>dual model</strong>: native/standard events remain strings; cross-team custom events could use Symbols where isolation matters. The polyfill bridges the gap.</p>


<h3>Notable Standard Gaps</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>No <code>CustomEventRegistry</code></strong> exists anywhere in WHATWG, WICG, W3C, or TC39 &mdash; the concept has not been proposed</li>
  <li><strong>No event namespace mechanism</strong> &mdash; the WHATWG DOM spec explicitly states namespace support "is not planned and will not be added"</li>
  <li><strong><code>EventTarget.getEventListeners()</code></strong> (<a href="https://github.com/whatwg/dom/issues/412">WHATWG #412</a>) &mdash; proposed in 2017 for listener introspection, still open with no consensus</li>
  <li><strong>Scoped Custom Element Registries</strong> (<a href="https://github.com/whatwg/html/issues/10854">WHATWG HTML #10854</a>) &mdash; for elements, not events, but establishes the pattern that scoping is needed</li>
  <li><strong>No proposal for Symbol-typed events</strong> &mdash; despite Node.js supporting them since v6. This could be a Web Everything contribution to standards discussion.</li>
</ul>


