<h3>Industry Trend</h3>

<p>A clear direction is emerging: <strong>frameworks are moving away from event abstractions</strong> toward typed function callbacks for component communication. DOM CustomEvents are increasingly reserved for cross-component or cross-library boundaries where framework abstractions can't reach.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Svelte 5 deprecated its event dispatcher</li>
  <li>Angular replaced EventEmitter with lightweight <code>output()</code></li>
  <li>Vue's emits are compile-time constructs, not DOM events</li>
</ul>

<p>Web Everything operates at the cross-library boundary by design (framework-agnostic blocks from different teams). This means we <strong>can't follow the framework trend</strong> of avoiding DOM events. We need DOM events to work correctly because that's our interop surface.</p>


<h2>The Core Challenge: Bubbling Collisions</h2>

<p>This is the <strong>most blocking element</strong>. All other problems (naming, typing, discoverability) are solvable with documentation and tooling. But bubbling collisions are a <em>runtime</em> problem that silently breaks applications.</p>

<h3>The Scenario</h3>

<p>When nested components emit identically-named events, listeners on ancestors fire for both. This is not hypothetical &mdash; it happens as soon as you compose blocks:</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!-- Outer component listens for "toggle" to track visibility --&gt;
&lt;div id="app"&gt;
  &lt;!-- A View-managed panel fires "toggle" --&gt;
  &lt;section view&gt;
    &lt;!-- A Popover inside fires "toggle" too --&gt;
    &lt;div popover&gt;...&lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  // This handler fires for BOTH toggle events!
  app.addEventListener('toggle', (e) =&gt; {
    // Is this the panel toggling or the popover toggling?
    // e.type is 'toggle' in both cases.
    // e.detail has the same shape in both cases.
    // Only e.target differs.
  });
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Today's Mitigations (All Inadequate)</h3>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Mitigation</th><th>Works?</th><th>Problem</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Check <code>event.target === event.currentTarget</code></td>
      <td>Partially</td>
      <td>Only works for direct children. Breaks with deeper nesting.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Check <code>event.eventPhase === Event.AT_TARGET</code></td>
      <td>Partially</td>
      <td>Same limitation. And consumers must remember to add the check.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Use <code>bubbles: false</code></td>
      <td>Yes, but&hellip;</td>
      <td>Prevents useful delegation patterns. Not always appropriate.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Module-prefixed names</td>
      <td>Yes, but&hellip;</td>
      <td>Convention-dependent. Doesn't solve same-name-different-source (View's <code>toggle</code> vs Popover's <code>toggle</code>).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>instanceof</code> check</td>
      <td>Yes, but&hellip;</td>
      <td>Fails across realms (iframes). Requires importing the Event class. Consumers must remember.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>The Key Insight</h3>

<p><strong>Two events with the same name being triggered is not a problem if only the correct listener answers.</strong></p>

<p>The real issue isn't the event name &mdash; it's that <code>addEventListener</code> only discriminates by string name. If listeners could filter by something <em>other</em> than name (event class, source block, protocol tag), name collisions would become irrelevant.</p>

<p>This reframes the problem: instead of preventing collisions at the <em>dispatch</em> side (naming), we can solve them at the <em>listener</em> side (discrimination).</p>


<h2>Exploration Axis 1: Listener Discrimination</h2>

<p>What if listeners could express <em>which</em> events they care about beyond just the name string?</p>


<h3>Approach A: Listen by Event Class Reference</h3>

<p>A utility or patched <code>addEventListener</code> that accepts an Event class instead of a string. Only events that are instances of that class trigger the handler.</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// blocks/tabs/events.ts
export class TabChangeEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;TabChangeEventDetail&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'tab-change';
  constructor(detail: TabChangeEventDetail) {
    super('tab-change', { bubbles: true, cancelable: true, detail });
  }
}

// Consumer — import the class, not a string
import { TabChangeEvent } from 'blocks/tabs';

// Option 1: Utility function (no patching needed)
listenFor(element, TabChangeEvent, (e) =&gt; {
  // e is typed as TabChangeEvent
  // Only fires for TabChangeEvent instances, not other 'tab-change' events
});

// Option 2: Patched addEventListener
element.addEventListener(TabChangeEvent, (e) =&gt; {
  // Same effect, more ergonomic
});</code></pre>

<p><strong>Implementation of <code>listenFor</code> is trivial:</strong></p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">function listenFor&lt;T extends Event&gt;(
  target: EventTarget,
  EventClass: { new(...args: any[]): T; readonly type: string },
  handler: (event: T) =&gt; void,
  options?: AddEventListenerOptions,
): () =&gt; void {
  const wrapper = (e: Event) =&gt; {
    if (e instanceof EventClass) handler(e as T);
  };
  target.addEventListener(EventClass.type, wrapper, options);
  return () =&gt; target.removeEventListener(EventClass.type, wrapper, options);
}</code></pre>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Assessment</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Collision safety</td><td>Full &mdash; <code>instanceof</code> is authoritative</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Type safety</td><td>Full &mdash; handler receives typed event</td></tr>
    <tr><td>No patching needed</td><td>Yes &mdash; <code>listenFor</code> is a pure utility</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Cross-realm</td><td>Theoretical concern &mdash; <code>instanceof</code> fails across iframes, but DOM events don't cross iframe boundaries (separate document trees, no shared elements). In practice, iframe communication uses <code>postMessage</code> (serialized data, no event objects). Not a real limitation for DOM events.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DevTools</td><td>Normal &mdash; standard addEventListener under the hood</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Third-party adoption</td><td>Requires importing Event classes. Third-party blocks must export them.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>


<h3>Approach B: Protocol-Tagged Events</h3>

<p>Events carry a protocol identifier (a string or Symbol) that listeners can filter on. This uses data comparison rather than object identity.</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// A well-known Symbol for tagging events with protocol identity
const EVENT_PROTOCOL = Symbol.for('we:event-protocol');

// blocks/tabs/events.ts
export class TabChangeEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;TabChangeEventDetail&gt; {
  [EVENT_PROTOCOL] = 'we:tabs:change';

  constructor(detail: TabChangeEventDetail) {
    super('tab-change', { bubbles: true, cancelable: true, detail });
  }
}

// Consumer — filter by protocol, not by class
element.addEventListener('tab-change', (e) =&gt; {
  if (e[EVENT_PROTOCOL] === 'we:tabs:change') {
    // This is definitely from the Tabs block
  }
});

// Or with a utility:
listenForProtocol(element, 'we:tabs:change', (e) =&gt; { ... });</code></pre>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Assessment</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Collision safety</td><td>Good &mdash; protocol strings are namespaced. Could also use Symbols for protocol IDs.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Cross-realm</td><td>Works in theory &mdash; <code>Symbol.for()</code> is shared across realms, protocol string is just data. But DOM events don't cross iframe boundaries anyway, so this advantage is moot for event discrimination.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Type safety</td><td>Partial &mdash; need to cast after filtering. Could use a typed map: <code>listenForProtocol&lt;TabChangeDetail&gt;(...)</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Standards path</td><td>Could propose extending <code>addEventListener</code> options: <code>{ protocol: 'we:tabs:change' }</code></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Discoverability</td><td>Events self-describe their source. Inspectable in DevTools via the property.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Overhead</td><td>Minimal &mdash; one property lookup per event dispatch</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>


<h3>Approach C: Scoped Listener Registration</h3>

<p>Instead of global <code>addEventListener</code>, listeners register through a scoped registry that knows which events belong to which blocks. The registry handles discrimination internally.</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// Each block registers its events in its own scope
const tabEvents = new EventScope('tabs');
tabEvents.define('change', { detail: TabChangeEventDetail, bubbles: true });

// Producer dispatches through the scope
tabEvents.dispatch(element, 'change', { from: 'a', to: 'b' });
// Under the hood: dispatches CustomEvent('tabs::change', ...)
// or adds a protocol tag, or uses a Symbol — the mechanism is hidden

// Consumer listens through the scope — no collision possible
tabEvents.on(element, 'change', (e) =&gt; {
  // Only receives events dispatched through the 'tabs' scope
});</code></pre>

<p>This is similar to CSS's <code>@scope</code> concept &mdash; the scope boundary determines which events are visible.</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Assessment</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Collision safety</td><td>Full &mdash; scopes are isolated by construction</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Micro-frontend safe</td><td>Yes &mdash; each MFE gets its own scope. Late-loading MFEs can't collide.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Underlying mechanism</td><td>Flexible &mdash; could use prefixed strings, Symbols, or protocol tags internally</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Global registry problem</td><td>Avoided &mdash; no single registry that all teams must coordinate through</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Ergonomics</td><td>Less familiar than <code>addEventListener</code>. Requires importing the scope.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Interop with native events</td><td>Separate &mdash; native events (<code>click</code>, <code>input</code>) stay on standard <code>addEventListener</code></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>


<h3>Approach D: Scoped Event Providers via Injectors</h3>

<p>This approach builds on a key observation: with the protocol-based architecture of Web Everything, the <strong>exact implementation is not known in advance</strong> and can vary per component or view. A modal could use the default implementation provided everywhere, or a specific component could use a custom implementation while still adhering to the same protocol. In both cases, the same event name might be triggered (e.g., <code>form:validated</code>, <code>modal:closed</code>).</p>

<p>The name itself cannot be relied upon &mdash; even if unlikely, unrelated components could trigger events with the same name. So we need to determine whether an event is "ours" &mdash; whether it came from a known, expected provider in the current scope.</p>

<p><strong>The insight:</strong> A global registry is problematic because of name collisions. But a <strong>scoped registry</strong> works if it "provides" a specific event class for a specific use case. And while we can't use a global registry, events <em>do</em> carry their <code>target</code> &mdash; which can be used to resolve the <strong>current scoped event provider</strong> for that specific element via the injector system.</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── A block provides its event class through the injector ──
// In a component's setup:
const injector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(this.element);
injector.set('customEvents:modal-closed', ModalClosedEvent);

// ── Another component deeper in the tree provides a different implementation ──
const childInjector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(this.childElement);
childInjector.set('customEvents:modal-closed', CustomModalClosedEvent);

// ── Consumer: use event.target to resolve the scoped provider ──
element.addEventListener('modal-closed', (event) => {
  // Ask the injector: "what event class is provided for 'modal-closed'
  // in the DOM scope of this event's target?"
  const ExpectedClass = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(
    event.target,
    'customEvents:modal-closed'
  );

  if (ExpectedClass && event instanceof ExpectedClass) {
    // This event came from a known provider in our scope.
    // Safe to handle — it's the implementation we expect.
    handleModalClosed(event);
  }
  // Otherwise: this is a 'modal-closed' event from an unknown source.
  // Ignore it — it's not ours.
});</code></pre>

<p>This is the same DOM-tree scoping pattern that the injector system already uses for services, stores, and contexts &mdash; extended to events. The key components:</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Event classes are provided through injectors</strong> &mdash; each block registers its event class in its scope, just like it registers stores or contexts.</li>
  <li><strong><code>event.target</code> is the resolution key</strong> &mdash; when an event arrives, its <code>target</code> tells us where in the DOM tree it originated. We walk the injector chain from that target to find the nearest provider for that event type.</li>
  <li><strong>Different scopes can provide different implementations</strong> &mdash; a top-level provider might supply a standard <code>ModalClosedEvent</code>, while a specific subtree provides <code>CustomModalClosedEvent</code>. The consumer doesn't need to know which one &mdash; the injector resolves the right class for the scope.</li>
  <li><strong><code>instanceof</code> validates the match</strong> &mdash; once we have the expected class from the injector, a standard <code>instanceof</code> check confirms the event came from a known provider.</li>
</ol>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── listenForScoped utility ──
function listenForScoped&lt;T extends Event&gt;(
  target: EventTarget,
  eventType: string,
  providerKey: string,
  handler: (event: T) =&gt; void,
  options?: AddEventListenerOptions,
): () =&gt; void {
  const wrapper = (e: Event) =&gt; {
    // Resolve the expected event class from the dispatch origin's scope
    const ExpectedClass = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(
      e.target as Element,
      providerKey,
    );
    if (ExpectedClass && e instanceof ExpectedClass) {
      handler(e as T);
    }
  };
  target.addEventListener(eventType, wrapper, options);
  return () =&gt; target.removeEventListener(eventType, wrapper, options);
}</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// Usage — works even when different subtrees provide different event classes
listenForScoped(
  document.querySelector('#app'),
  'modal-closed',
  'customEvents:modal-closed',
  (event) =&gt; {
    // Only fires when a 'modal-closed' event comes from an element
    // whose injector scope provides a matching event class.
    console.log('Modal closed:', event.detail);
  },
);</code></pre>

<h4>Why this works for protocol-based architecture</h4>

<p>In Web Everything, the same <em>protocol</em> (e.g., "a modal that can close") can be implemented by different blocks. Each implementation might dispatch a <code>'modal-closed'</code> event, but with its own event class. The injector system already solves this for services &mdash; a consumer asks "give me the modal service" and gets whatever was provided in scope. Scoped event providers extend this to events: a consumer asks "what event class represents modal-closed in this scope?" and validates incoming events against it.</p>

<p>This pattern is particularly powerful because:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>No global coordination needed</strong> &mdash; each scope declares its own event classes through the injector, just like it declares its own services.</li>
  <li><strong>Late-loading is safe</strong> &mdash; a new micro-frontend brings its own injector scope with its own event providers. These don't conflict with existing scopes.</li>
  <li><strong>Implementation swapping is transparent</strong> &mdash; if a subtree overrides the event provider (e.g., providing <code>CustomModalClosedEvent</code> instead of <code>ModalClosedEvent</code>), consumers using <code>listenForScoped</code> automatically validate against the right class.</li>
  <li><strong>No cross-realm limitation in practice</strong> &mdash; while <code>instanceof</code> fails across JavaScript realms (iframes), this is not a real concern for DOM events. Iframe boundaries are document boundaries: events dispatched inside an iframe stay in that iframe's document tree and don't bubble out to the parent. There are no shared DOM elements across realms. Iframe communication uses <code>postMessage</code>, which serializes data &mdash; no event objects cross. Shadow DOM, module federation, and dynamic imports all run in the same realm. For DOM event discrimination, <code>instanceof</code> is fully reliable.</li>
</ul>

