<h2>Exploration Axis 2: Symbol Events + Polyfill</h2>

<p>See the <a href="#symbol-events-via-polyfill-feasibility-study">Symbol feasibility study above</a>. The key question is whether the benefits of inherent Symbol uniqueness justify the costs (DevTools degradation, cross-realm complexity, incompatibility with declarative HTML).</p>

<p>The polyfill approach fits naturally into the plugs architecture. The "unplugged" mode would use string events with convention; the "plugged" mode would enable Symbol events with full collision safety.</p>

<p>A <strong>combined approach</strong> is possible: use Symbols for the event identity (collision safety) and attach a protocol tag for discoverability and documentation. Since DOM events don't cross iframe boundaries, the cross-realm question is moot &mdash; both Symbols and <code>instanceof</code> work reliably within a single document.</p>


<h2>Why a Global Registry Is Problematic</h2>

<p>A single <code>CustomEventRegistry</code> (analogous to <code>window.customElements</code>) seems attractive but has structural problems for micro-frontends:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>First-come-first-served</strong> &mdash; If Team A registers <code>'change'</code> and Team B tries to register <code>'change'</code> later, who wins? A throw breaks the late loader. Silent overwrite breaks the early one.</li>
  <li><strong>Load order dependency</strong> &mdash; Micro-frontends load in unpredictable order. A global registry creates implicit coupling between teams that have never coordinated.</li>
  <li><strong>No isolation</strong> &mdash; Every registration is visible to every consumer. A team's internal events pollute the global namespace.</li>
  <li><strong>Prefix registries?</strong> &mdash; Each registry could own a prefix (<code>tabRegistry.define('change')</code> &rarr; <code>'tabs:change'</code>). But without Symbols, a late-loading MFE could still claim the same prefix and throw. With Symbols, this problem disappears.</li>
</ul>

<p>If Symbols work (via polyfill), a global registry becomes unnecessary &mdash; Symbols are their own registry. If Symbols don't work, <strong>listener discrimination</strong> (protocol tags or scoped registries) provides isolation without a global coordination point.</p>


