<p>All of these fall back to string conventions. None provide structural isolation. The @trutoo/event-bus approach is the most rigorous (schema validation at registration time), but it still depends on unique string names.</p>


<h2>Recommendation</h2>

<p>One API covers all DOM event discrimination: <strong><code>listenForScoped</code></strong>. It uses <code>instanceof</code> to discriminate events, with the expected event class resolved at runtime from the injector scope of <code>event.target</code>. This is the same provide/resolve pattern the injector system already uses for stores, contexts, and services &mdash; extended to events.</p>

<p>The "build-time known class" case (what was previously <code>listenFor</code>) is simply <code>listenForScoped</code> where the event class happens to be registered at the document-level injector. No separate API needed &mdash; the registration cost is one <code>injector.set()</code> call, identical to what blocks already do for stores and contexts.</p>

<p>Convention-based naming (module-prefixed event names) is a complementary baseline: it reduces accidental collisions for consumers using plain <code>addEventListener</code>. Protocol tags are an optional documentation/introspection layer. Symbols and EventScope are unnecessary &mdash; <code>instanceof</code> already solves the discrimination problem without their costs.</p>


<h3>Shared Interfaces</h3>

<p>Both <code>listenFor</code> and <code>listenForScoped</code> build on a common event class contract:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">/**
 * Contract for a typed, self-describing custom event class.
 *
 * Every block event class implements this interface. The static `type`
 * property provides the string event name for addEventListener;
 * the class identity provides collision-safe discrimination via instanceof.
 */
interface TypedEventClass&lt;TDetail = unknown&gt; {
  /** The DOM event name string (e.g., 'tab-change', 'modal-closed'). */
  readonly type: string;

  /** Construct a new instance with the given detail payload. */
  new (detail: TDetail): TypedEvent&lt;TDetail&gt;;
}

/**
 * A CustomEvent instance that carries typed detail and is identifiable
 * by its class (instanceof) rather than by its string name alone.
 */
interface TypedEvent&lt;TDetail = unknown&gt; extends CustomEvent&lt;TDetail&gt; {
  readonly detail: TDetail;
}

/**
 * Return type for both listenFor and listenForScoped: a function that
 * removes the event listener when called.
 */
type Unsubscribe = () =&gt; void;</code></pre>


<h3><code>listenFor</code> &mdash; Lightweight Alternative</h3>

<p>A zero-infrastructure shortcut for when you have the event class in hand (direct import) and don't need injector-based resolution. Useful in unit tests, standalone utilities, or code that should not depend on the injector system. Not a separate tier &mdash; it's the same <code>instanceof</code> primitive without the injector lookup.</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">/**
 * Listen for events of a specific class. Only events that pass an
 * `instanceof` check against EventClass trigger the handler.
 *
 * @param target    - The element to listen on (can be an ancestor for delegation)
 * @param EventClass - The event class to discriminate by
 * @param handler   - Typed handler; receives the event as EventClass instance
 * @param options   - Standard addEventListener options
 * @returns Unsubscribe function that removes the listener
 */
function listenFor&lt;TDetail&gt;(
  target: EventTarget,
  EventClass: TypedEventClass&lt;TDetail&gt;,
  handler: (event: TypedEvent&lt;TDetail&gt;) =&gt; void,
  options?: AddEventListenerOptions,
): Unsubscribe;</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── Producer: define and export a typed event class ──
export interface TabChangeDetail {
  from: string | null;
  to: string;
  trigger: HTMLElement;
}

export class TabChangeEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;TabChangeDetail&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'tab-change';

  constructor(detail: TabChangeDetail) {
    super(TabChangeEvent.type, { bubbles: true, cancelable: true, detail });
  }
}

// Dispatch
tabGroup.dispatchEvent(new TabChangeEvent({ from: 'a', to: 'b', trigger: btn }));

// ── Consumer: import the class, get full type safety ──
import { TabChangeEvent } from 'blocks/tabs';

const unsub = listenFor(app, TabChangeEvent, (event) =&gt; {
  // event.detail is typed as TabChangeDetail
  // Only fires for TabChangeEvent instances — not for other 'tab-change' events
  console.log(`Tab changed from ${event.detail.from} to ${event.detail.to}`);
});

// Clean up
unsub();</code></pre>

<h4>When to use</h4>

<ul>
  <li>You <code>npm install @acme/tabs</code> and use it directly &mdash; import its event class</li>
  <li>You build components within the same project &mdash; import across modules</li>
  <li>You coordinate with another team on a shared package &mdash; the event class is the shared contract</li>
</ul>

<h4>Example: Nested discrimination</h4>

<p>Two blocks both fire events with the string name <code>toggle</code>. An ancestor listens for both without ambiguity:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// blocks/view/events.ts
export class ViewToggleEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;ViewToggleDetail&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'toggle';
  constructor(detail: ViewToggleDetail) {
    super(ViewToggleEvent.type, { detail });
  }
}

// blocks/dropdown/events.ts
export class DropdownToggleEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;DropdownToggleDetail&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'toggle';
  constructor(detail: DropdownToggleDetail) {
    super(DropdownToggleEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// ── Consumer: same string name, different classes, no ambiguity ──
import { ViewToggleEvent } from 'blocks/view';
import { DropdownToggleEvent } from 'blocks/dropdown';

listenFor(app, ViewToggleEvent, (e) =&gt; {
  console.log('Panel visibility:', e.detail.newState);
});

listenFor(app, DropdownToggleEvent, (e) =&gt; {
  console.log('Dropdown open:', e.detail.open);
});

// A native Popover 'toggle' event fires neither handler — it's a plain ToggleEvent,
// not an instance of ViewToggleEvent or DropdownToggleEvent.</code></pre>

<h4>Example: Lifecycle cleanup in a CustomAttribute</h4>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">import { TabChangeEvent } from 'blocks/tabs';

class MyBehavior extends CustomAttribute {
  #unsub?: Unsubscribe;

  connectedCallback() {
    // Listen on the closest ancestor — only TabChangeEvent instances fire
    this.#unsub = listenFor(this.target, TabChangeEvent, (e) =&gt; {
      this.#onTabChange(e.detail);
    });
  }

  disconnectedCallback() {
    this.#unsub?.();
  }

  #onTabChange(detail: TabChangeDetail) {
    // Guaranteed typed detail — no runtime shape checking needed
    console.log(`Switched to tab: ${detail.to}`);
  }
}</code></pre>

<h4>Example: Broadcast commands</h4>

<p><code>listenFor</code> also solves broadcast commands naturally. Dispatch on <code>document</code>, listen on <code>document</code>:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// commands/modals.ts
export class CloseAllModalsCommand extends CustomEvent&lt;void&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'close-modals';
  constructor() {
    super(CloseAllModalsCommand.type, { bubbles: false });
  }
}

// ── Any code can broadcast ──
document.dispatchEvent(new CloseAllModalsCommand());

// ── Every modal listens — only CloseAllModalsCommand instances trigger it ──
class ModalBehavior extends CustomAttribute {
  #unsub?: Unsubscribe;

  connectedCallback() {
    this.#unsub = listenFor(document, CloseAllModalsCommand, () =&gt; {
      this.#close();
    });
  }

  disconnectedCallback() {
    this.#unsub?.();
  }

  #close() { /* hide the modal */ }
}</code></pre>

<p>Other teams dispatching unrelated <code>'close-modals'</code> events won't trigger the handler &mdash; only <code>CloseAllModalsCommand</code> instances pass the <code>instanceof</code> check.</p>


<h3><code>listenForScoped</code> &mdash; The Primary API</h3>

<p>The single event discrimination API for Web Everything. The injector resolves the expected event class from <code>event.target</code>'s scope at runtime, then validates via <code>instanceof</code>. Covers all scenarios: same-project events (register at document level), plugin architectures (register per scope), broadcast commands (dispatch on <code>document</code>), and implementation swapping (different scopes provide different classes).</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">/**
 * Listen for events whose class is resolved at runtime from the
 * injector scope of the event's target element.
 *
 * When an event arrives, the injector is queried via event.target to
 * find the expected event class for this provider key. If found and
 * the event passes instanceof, the handler fires.
 *
 * @param target      - The element to listen on
 * @param eventType   - The DOM event name string to listen for
 * @param providerKey - The injector key that maps to the expected event class
 * @param handler     - Handler that receives the validated event
 * @param options     - Standard addEventListener options
 * @returns Unsubscribe function that removes the listener
 */
function listenForScoped&lt;TDetail&gt;(
  target: EventTarget,
  eventType: string,
  providerKey: string,
  handler: (event: TypedEvent&lt;TDetail&gt;) =&gt; void,
  options?: AddEventListenerOptions,
): Unsubscribe;</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── Provider A: standard modal implementation ──
export class ModalClosedEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;{ reason: string }&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'modal-closed';
  constructor(detail: { reason: string }) {
    super(ModalClosedEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// Registered in the injector at a scope boundary
const injector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(appRoot);
injector.set('customEvents:modal-closed', ModalClosedEvent);

// ── Provider B: custom modal in a different subtree ──
export class FancyModalClosedEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;{ reason: string }&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'modal-closed'; // Same DOM event name
  constructor(detail: { reason: string }) {
    super(FancyModalClosedEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// Different scope, different class for the same protocol
const childInjector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(widgetRoot);
childInjector.set('customEvents:modal-closed', FancyModalClosedEvent);

// ── Consumer: doesn't import any specific class ──
const unsub = listenForScoped(
  document.querySelector('#app'),
  'modal-closed',
  'customEvents:modal-closed',
  (event) =&gt; {
    // Fires for ModalClosedEvent from appRoot's scope
    // Fires for FancyModalClosedEvent from widgetRoot's scope
    // Ignores 'modal-closed' events from unknown sources
    console.log('Modal closed:', event.detail.reason);
  },
);</code></pre>

<h4>When to use</h4>

<ul>
  <li>A dashboard renders widgets it doesn't know about at build time &mdash; widgets are injected</li>
  <li>A form handles validation events from field implementations that may vary per deployment</li>
  <li>You build a framework layer where the concrete block is decided by the integrator, not by you</li>
  <li>You want to swap implementations (e.g., <code>@acme/modal</code> &rarr; <code>@other/modal</code>) without changing consumer code</li>
</ul>

<h4>Example: Plugin dashboard with unknown widgets</h4>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── Widget protocol: any widget can fire 'widget-action' ──
// Team A's widget
export class ChartActionEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;{ action: string; data: unknown }&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'widget-action';
  constructor(detail: { action: string; data: unknown }) {
    super(ChartActionEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// Team B's widget — different class, same event name
export class TableActionEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;{ action: string; data: unknown }&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'widget-action';
  constructor(detail: { action: string; data: unknown }) {
    super(TableActionEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// ── Each widget registers its event class in its own scope ──
// When team A's chart widget mounts:
const chartInjector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(chartContainer);
chartInjector.set('customEvents:widget-action', ChartActionEvent);

// When team B's table widget mounts:
const tableInjector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(tableContainer);
tableInjector.set('customEvents:widget-action', TableActionEvent);

// ── Dashboard: listens for all widget actions without importing any widget class ──
listenForScoped(
  dashboard,
  'widget-action',
  'customEvents:widget-action',
  (event) =&gt; {
    // Fires for ChartActionEvent from the chart scope
    // Fires for TableActionEvent from the table scope
    // Ignores 'widget-action' from an unknown third-party script
    console.log('Widget action:', event.detail.action, event.detail.data);
  },
);</code></pre>

<h4>Example: Swappable form field validation</h4>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── Two validation implementations that adhere to the same protocol ──

// Default: simple HTML5 validation
class SimpleValidationEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;{ valid: boolean; message?: string }&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'field-validated';
  constructor(detail: { valid: boolean; message?: string }) {
    super(SimpleValidationEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// Premium: schema-based validation with error codes
class SchemaValidationEvent extends CustomEvent&lt;{ valid: boolean; message?: string }&gt; {
  static readonly type = 'field-validated';
  constructor(detail: { valid: boolean; message?: string }) {
    super(SchemaValidationEvent.type, { bubbles: true, detail });
  }
}

// ── Deployer chooses which implementation to provide ──
const formInjector = InjectorRoot.getInjectorOf(formElement);
formInjector.set('customEvents:field-validated', SchemaValidationEvent);
// Swap to SimpleValidationEvent in a different deployment — no consumer changes.

// ── Form handler: doesn't care which validation is used ──
listenForScoped(
  formElement,
  'field-validated',
  'customEvents:field-validated',
  (event) =&gt; {
    if (!event.detail.valid) {
      showError(event.detail.message);
    }
  },
);</code></pre>

<h4>Example: Lifecycle in a framework layer</h4>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// A reusable container behavior that reacts to child events
// without knowing the concrete child implementations.
class ContainerBehavior extends CustomAttribute {
  #unsubs: Unsubscribe[] = [];

  connectedCallback() {
    // Listen for any 'item-selected' event from a known provider
    this.#unsubs.push(
      listenForScoped(this.target, 'item-selected', 'customEvents:item-selected', (e) =&gt; {
        this.#handleSelection(e.detail);
      }),
    );

    // Listen for any 'item-removed' event from a known provider
    this.#unsubs.push(
      listenForScoped(this.target, 'item-removed', 'customEvents:item-removed', (e) =&gt; {
        this.#handleRemoval(e.detail);
      }),
    );
  }

  disconnectedCallback() {
    this.#unsubs.forEach(unsub =&gt; unsub());
    this.#unsubs = [];
  }

  #handleSelection(detail: unknown) { /* ... */ }
  #handleRemoval(detail: unknown) { /* ... */ }
}</code></pre>


<h3>Plugged Mode: Browser-Native Ergonomics</h3>

<p>The examples above show <code>listenForScoped</code> as an <strong>unplugged</strong> utility &mdash; explicit import, standalone function. Web Everything's plugs architecture patches browser APIs to make features feel native. In plugged mode, event discrimination becomes a standard <code>addEventListener</code> option.</p>

<h4>Plugged <code>listenForScoped</code>: <code>addEventListener</code> with <code>provider</code> option</h4>

<p>The plug extends <code>AddEventListenerOptions</code> with a <code>provider</code> key. When present, the listener resolves the expected event class from <code>event.target</code>'s injector scope and validates via <code>instanceof</code> &mdash; all transparently.</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── The plug (applied by bootstrap.ts) ──
const origAddEventListener = EventTarget.prototype.addEventListener;
const origRemoveEventListener = EventTarget.prototype.removeEventListener;

// WeakMap to track wrapper functions for removeEventListener
const wrapperMap = new WeakMap&lt;Function, Map&lt;EventTarget, Function&gt;&gt;();

// ── Extended options interface ──
interface TypedEventListenerOptions extends AddEventListenerOptions {
  /**
   * Injector provider key. When set, the listener resolves the expected
   * event class from event.target's injector scope and applies instanceof
   * discrimination automatically.
   */
  provider?: string;
}

EventTarget.prototype.addEventListener = function(
  type: string,
  listener: EventListenerOrEventListenerObject | null,
  options?: boolean | TypedEventListenerOptions,
) {
  // Check for provider in options
  if (
    typeof options === 'object' &&
    options?.provider
  ) {
    const eventType = type;
    const providerKey = options.provider;
    const wrapper = (e: Event) =&gt; {
      const ExpectedClass = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(
        e.target as Element,
        providerKey,
      );
      if (ExpectedClass && e instanceof ExpectedClass) {
        (listener as EventListener)(e);
      }
    };
    if (!wrapperMap.has(listener as Function)) {
      wrapperMap.set(listener as Function, new Map());
    }
    wrapperMap.get(listener as Function)!.set(this, wrapper);
    return origAddEventListener.call(this, eventType, wrapper, options);
  }

  // Plain string — standard behavior
  return origAddEventListener.call(this, type, listener, options);
};</code></pre>

<p>With this plug applied, event discrimination feels like a native browser feature:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// ── Plugged mode: provider option on addEventListener ──

// Standard addEventListener call — the provider option triggers
// injector-based resolution at runtime
dashboard.addEventListener('widget-action', (event) =&gt; {
  // Only fires for events whose class matches the injector-provided
  // class at event.target's scope
  console.log('Widget action:', event.detail);
}, {
  provider: 'customEvents:widget-action',
});

// Form validation — swap implementations without changing this code
form.addEventListener('field-validated', (event) =&gt; {
  if (!event.detail.valid) {
    showError(event.detail.message);
  }
}, {
  provider: 'customEvents:field-validated',
});

// Standard string-based listener still works — no breaking change
app.addEventListener('click', (e) =&gt; {
  console.log('Clicked:', e.target);
});</code></pre>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;!-- Full plugged demo --&gt;
&lt;script type="module"&gt;
  // No imports needed for the listening side — just standard addEventListener
  // with an extra option. The plug + injector handle the rest.

  const dashboard = document.querySelector('#dashboard');

  // Discriminated listener — feels native
  dashboard.addEventListener('widget-action', (e) =&gt; {
    console.log('Action from widget:', e.detail.action);
  }, {
    provider: 'customEvents:widget-action',
  });

  // Meanwhile, each widget registers its event class through the injector
  // when it mounts — this is the provider side, unchanged from unplugged mode.
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>

<p>The key property: <strong>this is additive, not breaking</strong>. Passing no <code>provider</code> option works exactly as standard <code>addEventListener</code>. Adding the option enables discrimination transparently.</p>

<h4>Plugged mode summary</h4>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th></th><th>Unplugged (utility)</th><th>Plugged (patched API)</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Discriminated listener</strong></td>
      <td><code>listenForScoped(el, 'type', 'key', handler)</code></td>
      <td><code>el.addEventListener('type', handler, { provider: 'key' })</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Plain string</strong></td>
      <td><code>el.addEventListener('click', handler)</code></td>
      <td><code>el.addEventListener('click', handler)</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Cleanup</strong></td>
      <td><code>const unsub = listenForScoped(...); unsub()</code></td>
      <td><code>el.removeEventListener('type', handler)</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Imports needed</strong></td>
      <td><code>listenForScoped</code></td>
      <td>Nothing (just the provider key string)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Tree-shakeable</strong></td>
      <td>Yes</td>
      <td>No (global patch)</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The plugged version requires <strong>no new API to learn</strong> &mdash; it extends the existing <code>addEventListener</code> options object that every web developer already knows. The unplugged utility (<code>listenForScoped</code>) remains available for tree-shaking or environments where patching browser globals is undesirable. The lightweight alternative (<code>listenFor</code>) is available for code that should not depend on the injector system.</p>


<h3>Convention (Complementary Baseline)</h3>

<p>Module-prefixed naming reduces accidental collisions even for consumers using plain <code>addEventListener</code>. This is always applied as a baseline alongside <code>listenForScoped</code>:</p>

<pre><code class="language-text">Standard-aligned events:   Use the standard name (beforetoggle, toggle)
Module-scoped events:      module-eventname (tab-change, route-change)
Custom commands:           --module-action (--view-show, --tab-activate)</code></pre>

<p>Convention is belt-and-suspenders &mdash; it helps, but <code>instanceof</code> is the structural guarantee.</p>


<h3>Documentation Layer (Always)</h3>

<p>Regardless of which utility is used, blocks declare their events in the documentation layer (JSON + CEM):</p>

<pre><code class="language-json">{
  "events": {
    "tab-change": {
      "taxonomy": "notification",
      "detail": { "from": "string|null", "to": "string", "trigger": "HTMLElement" },
      "bubbles": true,
      "cancelable": true,
      "class": "TabChangeEvent",
      "provider": "customEvents:tab-change"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

<p>This enables tooling validation, documentation cross-references, and CEM generation. The <code>provider</code> field maps to the injector provider key used by <code>listenForScoped</code>.</p>


<h2>Open Questions</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>What do we call the three event categories?</strong> Notification / Targeted Command / Broadcast Command is the concept, but all three terms are overloaded. Need clear, unambiguous terminology that works in documentation, code, and conversation.</li>

  <li><strong>Should standard-aligned events (toggle, beforetoggle) use typed event classes?</strong> View's <code>toggle</code> deliberately matches the Popover API shape. Should View define a <code>ViewToggleEvent</code> class, or dispatch plain <code>CustomEvent</code> to stay aligned with the standard? If it uses a typed class, consumers using <code>listenForScoped</code> can distinguish View's toggle from Popover's &mdash; but should they?</li>

  <li><strong>How does <code>composed: true</code> interact with discrimination?</strong> Events crossing shadow DOM boundaries remain in the same realm (no <code>instanceof</code> issue), but <code>event.target</code> may be retargeted. Does <code>listenForScoped</code> need to account for composed event retargeting when resolving the injector scope?</li>

  <li><strong>How should <code>on:event</code> attributes integrate with <code>listenForScoped</code>?</strong> Declarative HTML attributes work with string names. Could a modifier like <code>on:tab-change.scoped="handler"</code> internally use <code>listenForScoped</code> with the element's injector scope? Or should declarative listeners always use plain <code>addEventListener</code>?</li>

  <li><strong>Can we align with CEM?</strong> The Custom Elements Manifest <code>events[]</code> field could be extended with <code>taxonomy</code>, <code>class</code>, and <code>provider</code> properties. This would benefit the entire web components ecosystem.</li>

  <li><strong>What should the provider key convention be?</strong> <code>'customEvents:modal-closed'</code> mirrors the existing <code>'customContexts:...'</code> pattern, but should the key be the event name, a protocol identifier, or something else? Should there be a <code>CustomEventProvider</code> registry parallel to <code>CustomStoreRegistry</code>?</li>
</ol>


<h2>Next Steps</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Implement <code>listenForScoped</code></strong> &mdash; Build the primary utility function. Test with different implementations in different scopes to validate injector-based discrimination and implementation swapping.</li>
  <li><strong>Convert existing events to typed classes</strong> &mdash; Replace inline <code>new CustomEvent()</code> calls in ViewEngine, TabGroupBehavior, and RouteViewElement with typed event classes that implement <code>TypedEventClass</code>. Register each in the injector at the appropriate scope.</li>
  <li><strong>Implement the <code>provider</code> plug</strong> &mdash; Patch <code>addEventListener</code> to accept the <code>provider</code> option for plugged mode.</li>
  <li><strong>Implement <code>listenFor</code></strong> &mdash; Build the lightweight alternative for use in unit tests and injector-free code.</li>
  <li><strong>Document event taxonomy</strong> &mdash; Add <code>taxonomy</code>, <code>class</code>, and <code>provider</code> fields to block event declarations in <code>blocks.json</code>. Establish terminology.</li>
  <li><strong>Test broadcast commands</strong> &mdash; Verify the <code>listenForScoped</code> + <code>document</code> pattern for broadcast commands (close all modals, pause all media).</li>
</ol>


<h2>Appendix: Naming Convention Prior Art</h2>

<p>For reference &mdash; the existing convention-based approaches in the wild. These are the <strong>last resort</strong> if structural solutions (listener discrimination, Symbols) prove unworkable.</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Pattern</th>
      <th>Example</th>
      <th>Used By</th>
      <th>Trade-offs</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Library prefix</td>
      <td><code>sl-change</code>, <code>sl-show</code></td>
      <td><a href="https://www.abeautifulsite.net/posts/why-you-should-prefix-custom-events/">Shoelace / Web Awesome</a></td>
      <td>Clear provenance. Verbose. Doesn't solve shared semantics.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Colon namespace</td>
      <td><code>my-lib:change</code></td>
      <td>Some community libs</td>
      <td>Structured. Not standard. Colon already used by attributes (<code>on:click</code>).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>No prefix</td>
      <td><code>change</code>, <code>toggle</code></td>
      <td>Native DOM, Lit examples</td>
      <td>Ergonomic. Highest collision risk.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Double-dash prefix</td>
      <td><code>--view-show</code></td>
      <td>Invoker Commands API</td>
      <td><strong>Strongest standard precedent.</strong> Browsers guarantee no built-in values start with <code>--</code>.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Custom Event subclass</td>
      <td><code>class TabChangeEvent extends Event {}</code></td>
      <td><a href="https://open-wc.org/guides/knowledge/events/">Open Web Components</a></td>
      <td>Disambiguates via <code>instanceof</code>. Doesn't prevent name collisions.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Convention works for a single team or coordinated teams. It does not scale to the cross-organization, multi-team scenario that Web Everything targets. If we resort to convention, it should be <em>in addition to</em> structural safeguards, not instead of them.</p>


